<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="371" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,1885,2019]" pageId="10" pageNumber="371">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1885,1911]" pageId="10" pageNumber="371">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The new species resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Holloway" authorityYear="1999" box="[587,711,1885,1911]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Leucoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="371" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ochripes">
<emphasis box="[587,711,1885,1911]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="371">L. ochripes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Bryk" authorityYear="1934" box="[764,875,1886,1911]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Leucoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="371" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="niveata">
<emphasis box="[764,875,1886,1911]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="371">L. niveata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in male genitalia, but can be easily separated from the latter two by the following characters: labial palpus white; middle and hind tarsi wihte, mixed with pale yellow scales; the left valva nearly rectangle, with a tiny plate of setea on inner surface; the right valva broad at basal half, narrow at distal half, densely covered with setea on cucullus; saccus small.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
